'''Beatrice Frederika Wright''', n<U+00E9>e '''Clough''', later '''Rathbone''' ([[17 June]] [[1910]] &ndash; [[17 Mar]] [[2003]]) was an [[United States|American]]-born [[United Kingdom|British]] politician.

She came to England to study at [[Ratcliffe College]], where she met and later married [[John Rathbone (Bodmin)|John Rathbone]], with whom she had two children, including [[Tim Rathbone|Tim]], later MP for Lewes.  Her husband was elected in 1935 as [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bodmin (UK Parliament constituency)|Bodmin]], but was killed in December 1940 in the [[Battle of Britain]], aged 30.  In March 1941 she was elected unopposed as his successor, and sat in the Commons for the rest of [[World War II]]. She stepped down at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1945|1945 general election]], after becoming the first sitting MP to give birth to a child.

In 1942, she remarried to [[Paul Wright (diplomat)|Paul Wright]], who had a distinguished career as a [[diplomat]] and was knighted in 1975. They had one child, and both converted to the [[Roman Catholic Church]].

She served as Vice President of the [[Royal National Institute for Deaf People|Royal National Institute for the Deaf]] from 1978 to 2003, and was a founder in 1982 of [[Hearing Dogs for Deaf People]], serving as the charity's President until 1988. In 1996, she was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]].

The Beatrice Wright Training Centre for [[hearing dog]]s, in [[Selby]], is named after her.

